 In the addendum to my short course book, several
 types of evolution are shown.  It turns out pretty
 ueasy to make detection of evolved programs NP-
 complete (or even exponential in same cases).  Here's
 a simple example:

 a, b, ...., x, y, z Original program ja, r, js, f,
 jg, a, jb, ..., j, jk Evolved program, where j* is a
 jump to the location of instruction *.  How about
 another?

           j=j+14
           k=j+120-(58*2);
           j=k;

 Another?

           a;
           b;
           c;
           d; is replaced by:
           a;
           call bb;
           c;
           call dd; dd:  d
           return bb:  b
           return

 Mix and match for mutations of mutations - call
 recursively for many more variations on the theme.
 For more details, read short course book (2nd
 release), or an upcoming paper in C+S (assuming they
 accept it) on program evolution.

