     Of course, we could just get rid of that little
message, couldn't we?  We know that when a critical
error occurs, Interrupt 24h is executed. If we were
to take over that Interrupt during virus execution,
and simply ignore all errors, allowing our
JumpCarry's to take us out of the code, we'd save
headaches (and pain), right?
     Okay, to accomplish that, we need to grab and
reset Interrupt 24h. Hmm, a call to Interrupt 21h,
Functions 35h (get) and 25h (put) would work, but
Anti-Virus programs watch those, so, even though DOS
manuals and Interrupt guides say not to (somebody HAS
to or it won't get done!!), let's modify the
interrupt table directly!
     The Interrupt Table begins at offset 0 of
segment 0, it's 256 addresses (Seg:Ofs) of the 256
interrupt handlers used by the CPU. To change one, we
need only to load the contents of the old register,
and put ours in, it's best accomplished like this:

 xor dx, dx
 push ds
 mov ds, dx

 les ax, word ptr ds:[24h*4]
 mov cs:[offset Int_24_Save],es
 mov cs:[offset Int_24_Save+2],ax

     Okay, there's the first part. The part with the
LES is courtesy of reading some of Dark Avenger, most
people use two Mov Word Ptr's, this is smaller.
     While we have our data segment as 0000, let's
set up our handler.

 cli
 mov ds:[24h*4], Cs
 mov word ptr ds:[24h*4+2], offset New_24h_Handler
 sti
 pop ds

     We want to keep our code modifying in a Cli/Sti
pair.  Although it's very unlikely an Int 24h could
be called during this code, it's possible that if you
were, say, modifying the keyboard interrupt's
address, a key could be pressed, the interrupt
called, and only the segment be changed.  The result,
a mess, and probably a crash (chances of hitting
menaingful code, doubtful!)
     The handler now. I want to thank Cavorting
Beastie for informing me that my old handler was
indeed a collosal fuckup, here's his version, which
WORKS!

handler proc near
 mov ax,3
 iret
 endp

     There it is, a simple process terminate flag in
Ax to cause DOS to stop trying whatever it is doing.
     On a write protected disk, you can open files
for read/write, so, that won't catch the error. The
place I've seen and found to be the best is the
setting of the file attributes. If there's an error,
you pretty well know that the file you're modifying
exists, so, it must be a write-protected. With our
handler in place, the error message is not shown, so,
a simple JC to the exit routine after the attribute
setting will end the routine. Make sure to close your
files, though!
